Aujeszky's disease, Finland
--------------------------
Information received on 24 Sep 2019 from Dr. Taina Aaltonen, Chief Veterinary Officer and Deputy Director General, Ministry of Agriculture and Forestry, Ministry of Agriculture and Forestry, Helsinki, Finland

Summary
Report type: immediate notification (final report)
Date of start of the event: 6 Sep 2019
Date of confirmation of the event: 23 Sep 2019
Reason for notification: 1st occurrence of a listed disease in the country
Causal agent: Aujeszky's disease virus
Nature of diagnosis: laboratory (advanced)
This event pertains to a defined zone within the country.

New outbreaks (1)
Outbreak location: Tohmajarvi, Ita-Suomi [North Karelia region]
Date of start of the outbreak: 6 Sep 2019
Outbreak status: resolved 23 Sep 2019
Epidemiological unit: forest
Total animals affected:
Species / Susceptible / Cases / Deaths / Killed and disposed of / Slaughtered
Wild boar: _Sus scrofa_ (Suidae) / - / 1 / - / - / -
Affected population: Hunted wild boar was found seropositive for Aujeszky disease.

Epidemiology:
Source of the outbreak(s) or origin of infection: Unknown or inconclusive.

Epidemiological comments: The case does not affect the official Aujeszky's disease-free status of Finland, since it was found in a wild boar. The domestic population remains free of AujeszkyÂ´s disease. All domestic pigs kept outdoors in Finland are protected from contact with wild boars by double-fencing.

Control measures
Measures applied: screening; vaccination prohibited; no treatment of affected animals

Measures to be applied: no other measures.

Diagnostic test results
Laboratory name and type: Finnish Food Authority (National laboratory)
Species / Test / Test date / Result
Wild boar / antibody detection ELISA / 17 Sep 2019 / Positive
Wild boar / real-time PCR / 11 Sep 2019 / Positive
Wild boar / virus neutralization test (VNT) / 23 Sep 2019 / Positive

Future reporting
The event is resolved. No more reports will be submitted.

[The location of the outbreak can be seen on the interactive map included in the OIE report at the source URL above.]

